{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17487359","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17487359"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T03:07:28+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T03:07:28+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"330"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"330","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/330"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.05,0.19,0.44,0.17,0.15]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"330"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"105800"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"330","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/330"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"330"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"88269"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"24"},{"type":"tags","id":"30"},{"type":"tags","id":"36"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"1061"},{"type":"tags","id":"1139"},{"type":"tags","id":"2136"},{"type":"tags","id":"2924"},{"type":"tags","id":"6376"},{"type":"tags","id":"12912"},{"type":"tags","id":"12919"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"11374"},{"type":"contributions","id":"11375"},{"type":"contributions","id":"38846"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"105800","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/105800"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 31-year-old man attends the Emergency Department with a six hour history of severe, colicky right loin pain going down into his groin. His blood pressure is 115/85 mmHg, pulse 100/min and temperature 37.8\u003Csup\u003Eo\u003C/sup\u003EC. His abdomen is soft. \u003Cbr /\u003E\u003Cbr /\u003EHis pain begins to settle with indomethacin and a CT scan is performed. This confirms the diagnosis of right-sided renal colic.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following CT findings would be the strongest reason for admission to hospital?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["A 5 mm stone in the lower ureter","A stone at the pelvi-ureteric junction","Stranding around the right kidney","A pelvic kidney","Mild hydronephrosis"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":[],"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe finding of \u003Cstrong\u003Estranding around the kidney\u003C/strong\u003E, in addition to a clinical picture of fever and any renal angle tenderness, would support a diagnosis of pyelonephritis and the need for antibiotics and inpatient urological consultation for consideration of lithotripsy or stenting (the latter if the kidney appeared to be obstructed). Whilst a solitary kidney might well be an indication for inpatient treatment of nephrolithiasis, one situated in the pelvis should not influence management. Mild hydronephrosis alone is not necessarily an indication for inpatient treatment, but should be considered with other factors such as stone size, location, and other co-morbidities when deciding on a management plan.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAn uncomplicated 5mm stone is not an indication for inpatient treatment. If the stone does not pass spontaneously, the patient may be referred for an outpatient urological opinion. A stone at the pelviureteric junction (PUJ) is not an indication for inpatient treatment, unless it was causing obstruction. Depending on stone size and composition, many of these stones at this site (PUJ) may pass spontaneously and those that do not, may be treated on an outpatient basis.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Peri-renal stranding seen on CT suggests pyelonephritis."],"references":["Vernuccio F, Patti D, Cannella R, Salvaggio G, Midiri M. CT imaging of acute and chronic pyelonephritis: a practical guide for emergency radiologists. Emerg Radiol. 2020 Oct;27(5):561-567. doi: 10.1007/s10140-020-01788-z. Epub 2020 May 22. PMID: 32445022. Available from: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/32445022/","Fulgham PF, Assimos DG, Pearle MS, Preminger GM. Clinical effectiveness protocols for imaging in the management of ureteral calculous disease: AUA technology assessment. J Urol 2013; 189:1203. Available from: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/23085059/","Morgan MSC, Pearle MS. Medical management of renal stones. BMJ 2016;352:52-63 Available from: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/26977089/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"88269"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"330"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"88269","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/88269"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-06-14T09:27:05+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-06-14T09:27:56+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"330"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"105800"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"24","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/24"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\ude91","name":"Emergency Medicine","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"5"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"30","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/30"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83c\udff4\u200d\u2620\ufe0f","name":"Radiology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-15T15:37:12+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags